'''Hugh IV of Saint-Pol''' (died March 1205 in [[Constantinople]]), son of [[Anselm of Saint-Pol]], was [[Count of Saint-Pol]] from 1174 to his death, and [[Lordship of Demotika|lord of Demotika]] in [[Thrace]] in 1204–05. He participated in the [[Third Crusade|Third]] and [[Fourth Crusade]]s.

== Life ==
He participated with [[Philip I, Count of Flanders]], in the [[Third Crusade]] where he distinguished himself in the [[Siege of Acre (1189–91)|siege of Acre]] in 1191.

In 1194 he received from [[Philip II of France]] the lands of [[Pont-Sainte-Maxence]], [[Verneuil-en-Halatte|Verneuil]] and [[Pontpoint]], because of his service.

In 1200 he enlisted in the [[Fourth Crusade]], where his prior service and rank made him among the leading non-Venetian nobles: he came fourth after [[Boniface of Montferrat]], [[Baldwin of Flanders]], and [[Louis I, Count of Blois|Louis of Blois]]. He participated in the [[siege of Constantinople (1204)|conquest of Constantinople]] on April 12, 1204, and received the sword of [[constable]] by the new [[Latin Emperor]], Baldwin of Flanders, who also gave him the fortress of [[Didymoteicho|Demotika]] in [[Thrace]].

He died of [[gout]] in 1205. He received a splendid funeral in [[Constantinople]] and his body was brought to [[France]] where he was buried in the [[Abbey of Cercamps]].

